04247nam a22005535i 9780773588561DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20132013xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807735885617 a10.1515/97807735885612doi  a(DE-B1597)655491  a(OCoLC)829421941  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aBX9881b.F53 2013 7aREL0150002bisacsh04a287.9/22231 aFlatt, Kevin N., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aAfter Evangelicalism :bThe Sixties and the United Church of Canada /cKevin N. Flatt. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2013] 4c©2013  a1 online resource (360 p.) :b2 tables  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aMcGill-Queen's Studies in the History of Religion ;v200tFront Matter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tSetting a Pattern, 1930–1940 -- tCalm before the Storm, 1940–1963 -- tCreating the New Curriculum, 1952–1964 -- tThe New Curriculum Controversy -- tA New Gospel: Theological Upheaval and Redefinition, 1959–1968 -- tThe “New Evangelism” and the “New Morality,” 1962–1971 -- tAftermath: The United Church and the Legacy of the Sixties -- tConclusion -- tThe Decision-Making Structure of the United Church -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAt a time when Canadians were arguing about the merits of a new flag, the birth-control pill, and the growing hippie counterculture, the leaders of Canada's largest Protestant church were occupied with turning much of English-Canadian religious culture on its head. In After Evangelicalism, Kevin Flatt reveals how the United Church of Canada abruptly reinvented its public image by cutting the remaining ties to its evangelical past. Flatt argues that although United Church leaders had already abandoned evangelical beliefs three decades earlier, it was only in the 1960s that rapid cultural shifts prompted the sudden dismantling of the church's evangelical programs and identity. Delving deep into the United Church's archives, Flatt uncovers behind-the-scenes developments that led to revolutionary and controversial changes in the church's evangelistic campaigns, educational programs, moral stances, and theological image. Not only did these changes evict evangelicalism from the United Church, but they helped trigger the denomination's ongoing numerical decline and decisively changed Canada's religious landscape. Challenging readers to see the Canadian religious crisis of the 1960s as involving more than just Quebec's Quiet Revolution, After Evangelicalism unveils the transformation of one of Canada's most prominent social institutions.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aEvangelicalismxUnited Church of CanadaxHistory. 0aEvangelicalismzCanadaxHistory. 0aÉvangélismexÉgise unie du CanadaxHistoire. 7aRELIGION / Christianity / History.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2013z978311127412608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2013z978311127715840uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978077358856140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780773588561423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780773588561/original  a978-3-11-127412-6  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2013b2013  a978-3-11-127715-8  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2013b2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles